(657, 657, 1, 'Chapter 25 Duality', 'I don’t know why it should be, I am sure; but the sight of another man asleep in bed when I am up, maddens me. It seems to me so shocking to see the precious hours of a man’s life- the priceless moments that will never come back to him again- being wasted in mere brutish sleep. –  – Jerome K. Jerome, Three men in a boat Duality is a transformation that maps lines and points into points and lines, respectively, while preserving some properties in the process. Despite its relative simplicity, it is a powerful tool that can dualize what seems like “hard ” problems into easy dual problems. 25.1 Duality of lines and points Consider a line ℓ ≡ y = ax + b in two dimensions. It is being parameterized by two constants a and b, which we can interpret, paired together, as a point in the parametric space of the lines. Naturally, this also gives us a way of interpreting a point as defining coefficients of a line. Thus, conceptually, points are lines and lines are points. Formally, the dual point to the line ℓ ≡ y = ax + b is the point ℓ ⋆  = (a, −b). Similarly, for a point p = (c, d) its dual line is p ⋆  = cx − d. Namely, p = (a, b)  ⇒ p ⋆ : y = ax − b ℓ: y = cx + d ⇒ ℓ ⋆  = (c, −d). We will consider a line ℓ ≡ y = cx + d to be a linear function in one dimension, and let ℓ(x)  = cx + d. A point p = (a, b) lies above a line ℓ ≡ y = cx + d if p lies vertically above ℓ. Formally, we have that b&gt; ℓ(a)  = ca + d. We will denote this fact by p ≻ ℓ. Similarly, the point p lies below ℓ if b &lt; ℓ(a)  = ca + d, denoted by p ≺ ℓ. A line ℓ supports a convex set S ⊆ IR 2 if it intersects S but the interior of S lies completely on one side of ℓ.', 'I don’t know why it should be, I am sure; but the sight of another man asleep in bed when I am up, maddens me. It seems to me so shocking to see the precious hours of a man’s life- the priceless moments that will never come back to him again- being wasted in mere brutish sleep. –  – Jerome K. Jerome, Three men in a boat Duality is a transformation that maps lines and points into points and lines, respectively, while preserving some properties in the process. Despite its relative simplicity, it is a powerful tool that can dualize what seems like “hard ” problems into easy dual problems.', 'Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor', 1315939088, 0),
